'''Telkom Media''' is a [[pay-TV]] company based in [[South Africa]]. It is intended to be the first provider of [[IPTV]] services in South Africa.
==History== South African fixed-line telephone operator [[Telkom SA|Telkom]] announced the creation of Telkom Media in August 2006, when it also applied for commercial satellite and cable-subscription broadcast licenses from the [[Independent Communications Authority of South Africa]].<ref>[[#MG1|M&G(1)]]</ref> Shareholders in the company included Telkom, [[Videovision Entertainment]], [[MSG Afrika Media]] and [[WDB Investment Holdings]].<ref>[[#MNY1|Moneyweb(1)]]</ref>
In April 2007 the company said it was conducting an internal IPTV trial.<ref>[[#MNY2|Moneyweb(2)]]</ref>
The total investment in startup was to amount to R7-billion, with R3.5-billion due to be sourced from Telkom.<ref>[[#MG3|Mail & Guardian(3)]]</ref>
Telkom Media received its licence in September 2007 in a process that included the award of three other new pay-TV licences.<ref>[[#IOL1|Independent Online(1)]]</ref>
===Attempted sale of Telkom stake=== In March 2008 Telkom said it would reduce its funding by R2.2-billion as other investments, such as a mobile wireless network, provided a shorter period for return.<ref>[[#MG3|Mail & Guardian(3)]]</ref>
In June 2008 Telkom said it intended to sell its (then 66 percent) stake in Telkom Media. By June it was said to have identified a buyer from among several interested parties<ref>[[#MG2|Mail&Guardian(2)]]</ref> and in November 2008 Telkom confirmed that negotiations were at an advanced stage.<ref>[[#BLM1|Bloomberg(1)]]</ref> The interested party was rumoured to be a South African consortium funded out of [[China]].<ref>[[#Times1|The Times(1)]]</ref>
In March 2009 the interested Chinese party was identified as the [[Shenzhen Media Group]] amid reports that negotiations had failed because Telkom sought compensation for its sunk investment in the business.<ref>[[#BR1|Business Report(1)]]</ref>
===Winding up and sale=== In late March 2009 Telkom said it had failed to find a buyer and intended closing down the company, having written down a R430-million [[shareholder loan]] to it.<ref>[[#REUT1|Reuters(1)]]</ref> The total costs of the company were estimated to be R700-million.<ref>[[#BD1|BusinessDay(1)]]</ref> A shareholder meeting to approve the shut down was due to be held before the end of April 2009.<ref>[[#BLM2|Bloomberg(2)]]</ref>
However, in early May 2009 Telkom announced that it had sold its stake to Shenzen Media, without immediately releasing further details.<ref>[[#MNY3|Moneyweb(3)]]</ref>
